 Hello and welcome to a walkthrough for Django for Everybody.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:11.500
 So the walkthrough that we're going to be doing is the walkthrough for the My Articles,

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:16.000
 which is really focusing on the notion of owning rows in a model.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
 And what I've got going here is I'm logged in twice.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
 I'm logged in one with a user ID of one, and the other is a user ID of two.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:31.000
 So let's just do a quick demonstration of what really owning rows in a model is.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
 So here I'm logged in as my first user, and now I'm logged in.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:39.000
 I'm using a separate browser, because this is Safari and this is Firefox.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:42.500
 You can't just do this with tabs, because the cookies are shared between tabs.

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:45.000
 And so you can log in and log out.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
 I want to just be logged in simultaneously.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
 And so I've got two of these tabs.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:00.000
 Refresh. So you'll notice that the edit and delete buttons show up differently for different users.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:07.000
 And that's because this row in the table lawnmower belongs to this user, user number two.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
 And these two rows belong to this user.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:21.000
 So if I take a look at administration and I go down into groups--not groups, not groups--users.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:24.000
 Now I can kind of hover, figure out that CSEV is two.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
 You can kind of see at the bottom there.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
 And DJ Furi is user one, and CSEV is user number two.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
 So those are the primary keys in Django's user table.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:43.000
 And now if I go and I take a look at these articles, you will see--and this looks a lot like if you were looking at, say, your autos.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
 Here's the rows or the models in articles.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
 And if I look at lawnmower, you see that there is a title, some text, and the owner is a dropdown.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
 And that's because this is a one-to-many field.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.000
 This is a one-to-many field between the articles and the users.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:10.000
 And then if I switch to a different--so that's CSEV.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:15.000
 So CSEV owns the lawnmower.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:19.000
 So I must be--I'm logged in as DJ Furi here.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.000
 No, here.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.000
 That's my name on DJ Furi.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.000
 And if I switch to Trombone, we'll see that that one belongs to DJ Furi.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
 Now I can sit and edit this in admin, right?

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:34.000
 But that's not the point.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
 The point is to build software.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:44.000
 If you'll notice, when I create a new article, it doesn't ask me what user it was, right?

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
 So this is where you would say Dodge or whatever when you were doing cars.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:03:02.000
 So this is like a race car, slightly used, Neon.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
 So now I have another one, right?

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:12.000
 And so the key thing was is it looks like a create from things we've done before.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
 Look at my articles. Here's this.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
 But somehow, magically, this owner field is populated.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:25.000
 And that's the essence of owned rows, is we've got a row, a column, and these are marked.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:33.000
 And we know in all our code, we know the difference, for example, between things we own and things we don't know--things we own and we don't own.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:43.000
 So if I hit refresh over here, there's a slightly used race car, but--slightly used race car, but I can't edit it, right?

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
 So that's the ownership.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
 Now, I don't know where to start.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:49.000
 There's a lot to cover here.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
 Let me show you--let me show--I don't know.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
 OK, I'll just start with--wait, we're always starting.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.000
 Let's start with--I'm running this locally.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
 I don't know what that bug is there.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:01.000
 That's not a bug.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.000
 So this is--just looks kind of like your autos.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.000
 If you look at it, it looks pretty much like the autos that might add a mileage or price in there or something.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
 The only thing that's really different at all is this.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:14.000
 There's a foreign key.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:17.000
 Now, in your autos, you have a foreign key to make.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:24.000
 And the key difference here--the only thing that's new is this idea of where the foreign key is pointing at.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:31.000
 Now, the problem is in Django, there is actually a table that all these users live in.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.000
 And I can probably come over here and type tables.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:35.000
 And I can see it.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:37.000
 I think it's probably here.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:45.000
 So let's just try saying select star from auth user.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.000
 So we should see a bunch of rows.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
 And so there are my users.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:54.000
 CSEV, you kind of--it's all jammed together in DJ4E.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
 So this is row one for DJ4E and CSEV.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
 So there is a table and a model.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:08.000
 The difference is we're not allowed to know that this is the user model in the auth application.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
 And so what happens is we have to let Django tell us what the name of that model is.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
 And so we go into settings, which is settings.py, actually.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
 And we're going to pull in the settings.py.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
 And the default is auth user model.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
 And that's the name of the model.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
 And so this is the foreign key to a place that we don't exactly know,

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
 but Django will tell us and put in a string here.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
 If we were to print this out, we would see what that is.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
 That's just a string, but it's not a string we mess with.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
 On delete cascade, that's just normal.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
 The kind of parent row, the one row is in users.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.000
 And if you delete a user, that means that all of the rows that belong to that user will get deleted

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:49.000
 because on delete cascade.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:51.000
 I'm choosing that as the model.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:59.000
 And so you see created at, if we go back into the-- you see all of these things.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.000
 Now created at, admin doesn't show.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
 It's pretty smart knowing about created at and update.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
 So it doesn't bother doing that.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
 And it actually updates them automatically.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.000
 So it knows something about created at and updated at in admin.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
 So that is our model.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:24.000
 If we were to take a look at myarts.Article,

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
 you will see that there is a foreign key right there.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:29.000
 There's a foreign key.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:40.000
 And if we say select star from myarts.Article, you will see that there is a foreign key in there.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
 So this row belongs to user one.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:43.000
 This row belongs to user one.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
 That row belongs to user two.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.000
 And that row belongs to user one, which is perfectly reflected here.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.000
 So now I am user one, so I can edit three of them.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
 Now I am here with user two, and I can edit one of them.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
 So I'm editing the ones where I own it.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:04.000
 So ultimately, we're going to write a bunch of code so that these numbers are properly updated.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
 So when you add the article, it works the way you want it to work.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
 So let's just take a look at urls.py.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
 It's pretty boring.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
 This looks just like autos.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:23.000
 I probably hoisted up success URL here, put that in the as view as a parameter.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
 And so that makes my views even simpler.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.000
 myarts colon all points to that view.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:37.000
 I think it actually is kind of prettier to put it in here because this is sort of a URL place.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.000
 And so it's not in my view.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
 So that makes my views really succinct.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:53.000
 And so it's like what you did once you got your autos down to just using the generics.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:58.000
 And so I have a list, a detail, a create, an update, and a delete.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:02.000
 And I have a model called article, which I just showed you.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:08.000
 And I am going to reuse some general purpose views for owner kinds of rows.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
 Now, these are not from Django, these are from me.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:13.000
 I made them.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
 And now I'm using them.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
 So article list view extends owner list view.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
 And then I can put all my things in there.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:25.000
 The success URL, actually, I don't need that here.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
 But for create view, I do need a success URL.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
 But for create view, that success URL comes right from here.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
 So I could have put it either here or I could have put it here.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
 For me, after a while, I think this is prettier.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:45.000
 Because now I can look at all the names of my arts, et cetera.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:46.000
 So that's kind of nice.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.000
 OK.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
 So here's views.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:51.000
 We're going to come back to this.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:56.000
 All the brains of this operation are in owner list view, owner detail view, create view, update view.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
 And we'll look at that last.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
 So that's where the hardest part is.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
 But let's first look at the template.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
 And so here's the template.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:09.000
 This looks a lot like your autos.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:17.000
 The only real difference here is that this edit and delete button is inside of an if statement.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
 So it's article update, article ID, article delete, article ID.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:22.000
 That's the same.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
 You've done that, right?

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:32.000
 But all it says is if article.owner is equal to the current logged in user, article.owner is one of the article lists.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
 That's just one of the fields in the model, which happens to be a number.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
 But we're giving this user for free, right?

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:43.000
 It just hands us user, and so we can compare it.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:48.000
 So if this is one that we own, we show this link.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
 And if it's not one that we own, we don't show the link, right?

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
 So we don't show the link for the ones that we own.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:02.000
 Now, I hope by now you realize that we have to also protect, right?

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
 So this is number four, right?

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
 And if I click edit, number five.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
 But what if I just change this to four?

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:20.000
 We still just not putting up the link does not mean that we can't have someone go to that link.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
 So I'm cheating by putting in this link, but this is going to blow up, right?

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:30.000
 And so we'll show you how just because you don't put the link up doesn't mean that people can't go to the link.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
 They can guess what the link is.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
 I just did that.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
 I went to an article I could update.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
 I noticed the primary key of one I could not update to be four.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:46.000
 And then I went to five, and then I just edited it, changed it to four, and I attempted to update four.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
 So it's not good enough just to not show the link.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
 That's actually not security.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
 That just is prettiness, usability.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
 Don't show a link that is going to blow up if you click on it.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
 So that's not really protecting us.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:05.000
 This if statement is not really protecting us from clicking on or attempting to go edit or delete.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
 It's just not showing it if it's not going to work.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.000
 OK.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:18.000
 And again, article.owner is just a column in this model, and user is the current logged in user.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
 OK.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
 OK.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:31.000
 So what we'd seen before is I would create a view and then use it in my urls.py, and it would extend another view.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.000
 So now it's time to take a look at where this view is being defined.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:41.000
 And so here's our view, generic view, the New York list view, delete view.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.000
 These are the generic ones.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:49.000
 And all I'm really doing here is I'm creating a class called owner list view that extends list view.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
 Now, it pulls in everything that list view is.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
 And you'll notice I've added nothing to it.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:59.000
 And I really could because the list view doesn't really care.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.000
 It's not really doing anything other than the fact that that value is in the models.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
 So it's going to come in.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.000
 So I could have made this be list view, but I just want it to be pretty.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.000
 I want to make it so that I could just say owner list view, owner detail view.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:20.000
 And so you'll notice that I'm not making any changes at the moment of inheritance.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
 I'm not changing owner.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:28.000
 So owner list view is exactly the same as list view, and owner detail is exactly the same as detail.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:33.000
 I just did it to make it pretty in case later maybe I want to add some.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
 But now we get to owner create view.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:41.000
 Owner create view is something that matters a lot.

